<treatment id="03E38A4C86396664FF5B77B0FA7CC61C" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5449459" ID-GBIF-Taxon="119622158" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5449459" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03E38A4C86396664FF5B77B0FA7CC61C" httpUri="http://treatment.plazi.org/id/03E38A4C86396664FF5B77B0FA7CC61C" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<subSubSection id="C35068D186396664FF5B77B0FD2DC3C7" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B77B0FC87C2CA" blockId="3.[151,864,151,177]" box="[151,864,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading id="D0BD8C3686396664FF5B77B0FC87C2CA" bold="true" box="[151,864,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FF5B77B0FC87C2CA" bold="true" box="[151,864,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Key to the species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4A40D986396664FE5077B0FDFBC2CA" box="[412,540,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FE5077B0FDFBC2CA" bold="true" box="[412,540,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Megalopta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occuring in Minas Gerais
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B77C6FC35C333" blockId="3.[151,1436,225,328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Although this study focused on the species of Minas Gerais, the present key includes all species currently known to occur in the Southeastern and Southern Regions of 
<collectingCountry id="F35D7BCA86396664FC4E762FFC2BC359" box="[898,972,264,290]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(states of Santa Catarina, Paraná, São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro and Espírito Santo, in addition to Minas Gerais).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B765BFF1EC3ED" blockId="3.[151,714,380,444]" box="[151,249,380,406]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Females</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B7685FD2DC3C7" blockId="3.[151,714,380,444]" box="[151,714,418,444]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
[unknown for 
<taxonomicName id="4C4A40D986396664FEF27685FD9EC3C0" box="[318,633,418,443]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantica" status="sp. n." subGenus="Noctoraptor">
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FEF27685FD9EC3C0" box="[318,633,418,443]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. (Noctoraptor) atlantica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A20D5A3386396664FD4D7685FD27C3C7" box="[641,704,418,444]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35068D186396664FF5B76D7FA7CC61C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="key">
<keyStep id="30BE23FF86396664FF5B76D7FA72C09C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B76D7FA7CC01C" blockId="3.[151,1436,496,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="30BB986F86396664FF5B76D7FA7CC01C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<number id="3D82297D86396664FF5B76D7FF43C07C" box="[151,164,496,519]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
Lateral surface of metapostnotum reticulate at least along its posterior margin, sometimes rugulose on the lateralmost section of the anterior margin; posterior margin of metapostnotum straight or gently arcuate, gradually curved towards the anterior margin laterally (
<figureCitation id="137127DF86396664FDAC7517FD4BC03C" box="[608,684,560,583]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,255,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[172,1414,185,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[172,1415,185,1690]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Megalopta aegis (Vachal, 1904), female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma. FIGURE 4. Megalopta sodalis (Vachal, 1904), female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma. FIGURE 5. Megalopta amoena (Spinola, 1853), female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma. FIGURE 6. Megalopta guimaraesi sp. n., female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189462/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FD517517FD4BC03C" box="[669,684,560,583]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.4">3</number>
</figureCitation>
, 4); disc of scutellum convex, dorsal surface of axilla and contiguous antero-lateral margin of scutellum below level of disc of scutellum as seen from behind .......................................... 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FA427577FA7CC01C" box="[1422,1435,592,615]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B7557FA72C09C" blockId="3.[151,1436,496,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="30BB986F86396664FF5B7557FA72C09C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Lateral surface of metapostnotum polished, although sometimes minutely punctate; posterior margin of metapostnotum straight, abruptly bending laterally toward metanotum (Figs. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FC4E75B7FC4BC0DC" box="[898,940,656,679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.6">5, 6</number>
); disc of scutellum uniformly flat or very gently arcuate, dorsal surface of axilla and contiguous antero-lateral margin of scutellum on same or almost on same plane as disc of scutellum as seen from behind ........................................................................................................... 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FA4475F7FA72C09C" box="[1416,1429,720,743]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.0">3</number>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30BE23FF86396664FF5B75D7FA7CC1BC" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B75D7FA7CC11C" blockId="3.[151,1436,496,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="30BB986F86396664FF5B75D7FA7CC11C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<number id="3D82297D86396664FF5B75D7FF43C17C" box="[151,164,752,775]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
Metepisternal process conspicuous, wide, with velvety pilosity (
<figureCitation id="137127DF86396664FCB675D7FC5EC17C" box="[890,953,752,775]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,257,1715,1739]" captionText="FIGURE 1. Megalopta guimaraesi sp. n., female: lateral view of mesosoma. The arrow indicates the metepisternal process." pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FC6175D7FC5EC17C" box="[941,953,752,775]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); longitudinal rugae of metapostnotum short throughout its surface, not reaching its posterior margin, normally stronger laterally (
<figureCitation id="137127DF86396664FB9E7437FB74C15C" box="[1106,1171,784,807]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,255,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[172,1414,185,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[172,1415,185,1690]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Megalopta aegis (Vachal, 1904), female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma. FIGURE 4. Megalopta sodalis (Vachal, 1904), female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma. FIGURE 5. Megalopta amoena (Spinola, 1853), female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma. FIGURE 6. Megalopta guimaraesi sp. n., female: postero-lateral view of mesosoma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189462/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FB487437FB74C15C" box="[1156,1171,784,807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
); disc of metapostnotum slightly convex, its posterior margin frequently depressed in relation to contiguous surface of propodeum ............... 
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FF027477FB1FC11C" box="[206,1272,848,871]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
.................................................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4A40D986396664FB507477FB1FC11C" authority="Vachal, 1904" authorityName="Vachal" authorityYear="1904" box="[1180,1272,848,871]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegis">M. aegis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDB46AB86396664FACA7477FA73C11C" author="Vachal" box="[1286,1428,848,871]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" refString="Vachal, J. (1904) Etude sur les Halictus d´Amerique (Hym.). Miscellanea Entomologica, 12, 113 - 115." type="journal article" year="1904">
Vachal, 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FA927477FA73C11C" box="[1374,1428,848,871]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1904.0">1904</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B7457FA7CC1BC" blockId="3.[151,1436,496,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="30BB986F86396664FF5B7457FA7CC1BC" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Metepisternal process inconspicuous, narrow and without velvety pilosity (
<figureCitation id="137127DF86396664FC3D7457FBD3C1FC" box="[1009,1076,880,903]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,255,1785,1809]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalopta sodalis (Vachal, 1904), female: lateral view of mesosoma. The arrow indicates the metepisternal process." pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FBE87457FBD3C1FC" box="[1060,1076,880,903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
); longitudinal rugae of metapostnotum stronger in the mid triangular depression, longer medially, shortening laterad (Fig. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FB4974B7FB72C1DC" box="[1157,1173,912,935]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="4.0">4</number>
); disc of metapostnotum concave, its posterior margin at same level or above contiguous surface of propodeum 
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FBAA7497FB1EC1BC" box="[1126,1273,944,967]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
.... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4A40D986396664FB457497FB1EC1BC" authority="Vachal, 1904" authorityName="Vachal" authorityYear="1904" box="[1161,1273,944,967]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sodalis">M. sodalis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDB46AB86396664FACA7497FA73C1BC" author="Vachal" box="[1286,1428,944,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" refString="Vachal, J. (1904) Etude sur les Halictus d´Amerique (Hym.). Miscellanea Entomologica, 12, 113 - 115." type="journal article" year="1904">
Vachal, 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FA927497FA73C1BC" box="[1374,1428,944,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1904.0">1904</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30BE23FF86396664FF5B74F7FA7CC61C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B74F7FA7BC67C" blockId="3.[151,1436,496,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="30BB986F86396664FF5B74F7FA7BC67C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<number id="3D82297D86396664FF5B74F7FF43C19C" box="[151,164,976,999]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.0">3</number>
Metepisternal process, inconspicuous, narrow, without velvety pilosity (
<figureCitation id="137127DF86396664FC1874F7FBF0C19C" box="[980,1047,976,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,255,1785,1809]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalopta sodalis (Vachal, 1904), female: lateral view of mesosoma. The arrow indicates the metepisternal process." pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FBCB74F7FBF0C19C" box="[1031,1047,976,999]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
); longitudinal rugae of metapostnotum absent, ferruginous with metallic green hues restricted to lateral areas .................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4A40D986396664FBBB74D7FA7BC67C" authority="Spinola, 1853" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1853" box="[1143,1436,1008,1031]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amoena">
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FBBB74D7FB17C67C" box="[1143,1264,1008,1031]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. amoena</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDB46AB86396664FB3274D7FA73C67C" author="Spinola" box="[1278,1428,1008,1031]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" refString="Spinola, M. (1853) Compte rendu des Hymenopteres inedits provenants du voyage entomologique de M. Ghiliani dans le Para en 1846. Memorie della Reale Academia delle Scienze di Torino, 2, 19 - 94" type="journal article" year="1853">
Spinola, 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FA9274D7FA73C67C" box="[1374,1428,1008,1031]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1853.0">1853</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF53B5A86396664FF5B7337FA7CC61C" blockId="3.[151,1436,496,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="30BB986F86396664FF5B7337FA7CC61C" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Metepisternal process, conspicuous, wide, covered by velvety pilosity (
<figureCitation id="137127DF86396664FC167337FBFCC65C" box="[986,1051,1040,1063]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,257,1715,1739]" captionText="FIGURE 1. Megalopta guimaraesi sp. n., female: lateral view of mesosoma. The arrow indicates the metepisternal process." pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number id="3D82297D86396664FBC37337FBFCC65C" box="[1039,1051,1040,1063]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); metapostnotum with at least one weak but distinct mid-longitudinal ruga, shiny, entirely and homogeneously green, light brown or black ................... 
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FF027377FABEC61C" box="[206,1369,1104,1127]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
....................................................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C4A40D986396664FB727377FABEC61C" box="[1214,1369,1104,1127]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guimaraesi" status="sp. n.">M. guimaraesi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B93EE74886396664FAAC7368FA7CC61C" bold="true" box="[1376,1435,1103,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A20D5A3386396664FAAC7368FA7CC61C" box="[1376,1435,1103,1127]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
